```suggestion
lemma hasCardinalLT_arrow_op_iff (C : Type u) [Category.{v} C] (Îº : Cardinal.{w}) :
```

It's really sad that making this equivalence explicit is so painful. Do we have any idea how to improve things? Creating a structure for morphisms in induced categories might help a bit, but probably it would be painful even then.

In any case, I think it would be good to generalize this to arbitrary equivalences of types and put it next to `Equivalence.inducedFunctorOfEquiv`.

I tried putting morphisms in induced categories into a structure on the branch `induced-struct`, and indeed then you can construct the equivalence as
```lean
def induced {C' : Type*} (e : C' â‰ƒ D) : InducedCategory D e â‰Œ D where
  functor := inducedFunctor e
  inverse :=
    { obj := e.symm
      map {X Y f} := âŸ¨eqToHom (by simp) â‰« f â‰« eqToHom (by simp)âŸ© }
  unitIso := NatIso.ofComponents (fun X => eqToIso (by simp))
  counitIso := NatIso.ofComponents (fun X => eqToIso (by simp))
```
Of course, this is a large change and there is fallout. All of the bad fallout I've seen so far is in concrete categories, and it is my understanding that a lot will change there with Anne's refactoring, so I'm not sure if it would make sense to push through with changing `InducedCategory` while the concrete category refactor is in progress.

At some point, I had started doing the refactor of induced/full subcategories, but I had let it bitrot too soon. This may also interact with Anne's refactor of concrete categories. Until these refactors are done, we may probably proceed with the more general equivalence you suggested #20881 (the code does not seem too terrible...), and it will be easy to do a cleanup when the refactors are done.
